  <entry>
    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w35078</id>
    <title>The “Peace Dividend” of International Trade: A New Empirical Approach</title>
    <updated>2026-04-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Ling Feng, Qiuyue Huang, Zhiyuan Li &amp; Christopher M. Meissner</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This paper investigates the causal impact of international trade on interstate military conflicts using global bilateral data from 1962 to 2014. To address endogeneity concerns, we exploit exogenous spatial-temporal variation in international trade stemming from technological advances in air relative to maritime transport. Empirical results demonstrate a strong “peace dividend” of international trade: that is, increased trade significantly reduces the probability and intensity of conflicts between nations. This effect remains robust across specifications and withstands a wide range of potential confounders. Such findings highlight how economic interdependence shapes international conflict—a relationship that is especially relevant amid escalating geopolitical tensions and the global shift toward “decoupling”, “de-risking”, and greater trade protectionism.</content>
    <link href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w35078"/>
    <category term="NBER"/>
    <published>2026-04-01T00:00:00+00:00</published>
